issue.title: FetchHttpClient is preventing NextJS from caching responses
issue.body:
### What version of Effect is running?

3.15.4

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

1. Create a `HttpClient` for fetching data
2. Create a `NextFetchHttpClientLive` from `FetchHttpClient.layer`
3. Set caching rules in `FetchHttpClient.RequestInit` for `cache: "force-cache"`
4. Call the `HttpClient` in an effect
5. Run the effect in a managed runtime
6. Refresh the page to see if the results are cached
7. ❌ Get cached results

### What is the expected behavior?

When using the fetch outside of the `HttpClient` the response should be cached and return the first response until invalidated.  This can also be checked in the log to see if the cache was hit:
```sh
GET / 200 in 1141ms
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke 200 in 1ms (cache hit)
```

### What do you see instead?

Instead I get a new response and can see in the logs that the cache was missed:
```sh
 GET / 200 in 1141ms
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=http 200 in 1100ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))
```

### Additional information

Brought this up [on Discord](https://discord.com/channels/795981131316985866/1362759766866399262) but didn't get anywhere.  Since then have been checking all the latest versions of Next and Effect to see if something changes, but still broken.

Have tested using fetch in effect without `HttpClient` and  in a `Effect.tryPromise` and can successfully get Next to trigger the cache so something magical is happening in `HttpClient`:

```sh
# Force-Refresh browser 

 GET / 200 in 1165ms
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=http 200 in 205ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=typPromise 200 in 206ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke 200 in 1128ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=assign 200 in 1133ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))

# Trigger Refresh

 GET / 200 in 1141ms
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke 200 in 1ms (cache hit)
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=typPromise 200 in 0ms (cache hit)
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=assign 200 in 0ms (cache hit)
 │ GET https://official-joke-api.appspot.com/random_joke?r=http 200 in 1100ms (cache skip)
 │ │ Cache skipped reason: (cache-control: no-cache (hard refresh))
```

https://github.com/lloydrichards/min_next-fetch-effect

Can try it out yourself 👆

issue.title: Fixes #1246 and #1756 - Removed Hall of Fame task
issue.body:
- Fixes #1246 and #1756

Todo:
- [X] Migration
- [x] _New_: use of [django-pgtrigger](https://django-pgtrigger.readthedocs.io) (note this does [add some overhead/boilerplate](https://github.com/AmbitionEng/django-pgtrigger/blob/2ba6f78e7da344e562ecfde0d4ec21eba646a2bf/pgtrigger/compiler.py#L42-L75) to support the [`pgtrigger.ignore`](https://django-pgtrigger.readthedocs.io/en/4.15.2/module/#pgtrigger.ignore) decorator to dynamically [Ignoring Execution](https://django-pgtrigger.readthedocs.io/en/4.15.2/ignoring_triggers/) of the triggers)
- [X] Rewrite `update.py` to use `Fame` model
- [X] _New:_ rewrite `update.py` + Redis cache + #1756 to `interface/views/__init__.py`
    Already cached via [`@simple_cache_page`](https://github.com/internetstandards/Internet.nl/blob/917b8219a7ce451b5b33cfe7ba46ea323bf72436/interface/__init__.py#L30-L54) in Redis
- [x] _New:_ check if instead of requesting once from the DB and sorting in application space the DB can be requested 3 times with the sorted output, so the `iterator()` can be used without sorting in Python, this would save memory (and probably faster to sort at the DB, since there it's also possible to add indices). Check if permalink formatting can be done generic and done at a point to minimize string copying.
- [ ] Optional: put `slow-worker` in some sort of compose `batch` profile (since the 2-5GB memory container won't be needed in Single Test mode), or move remaining slow-worker tasks (registering and generating async results) to another container
- [x] Find a way to remove the `SELECT "checks_fame"."id"` (while `.only("domain")`) for Index Only Scan performance for HoF queries (fixed by using domain as primary key in django, note this does create an extra `"checks_fame_domain_HASHHASH_like" btree (domain varchar_pattern_ops)` index)
- [ ] Test
  - [X] Enable PostgreSQL query log (make sure the ForeignKey doesn't actually fetch the related report model)
  ```bash
  docker compose --env-file docker/develop.env exec postgres psql -Uinternetnl internetnl_db1 -c "ALTER SYSTEM SET log_statement TO 'all';" -c "SELECT pg_reload_conf();"
  docker compose --env-file=docker/defaults.env --env-file=docker/develop.env logs postgres -f
  ```
  Seems okay:
  ```none
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.082 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: BEGIN
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.082 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: DECLARE "_django_curs_140058792129024_sync_1" NO SCROLL CURSOR WITHOUT HOLD FOR SELECT "checks_fame"."id", "checks_fame"."domain", "checks_fame"."site_report_id", "checks_fame"."site_report_timestamp", "checks_fame"."mail_report_id", "checks_fame"."mail_report_timestamp" FROM "checks_fame"
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.084 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: FETCH FORWARD 2000 FROM "_django_curs_140058792129024_sync_1"
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.085 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: FETCH FORWARD 2000 FROM "_django_curs_140058792129024_sync_1"
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.085 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: CLOSE "_django_curs_140058792129024_sync_1"
  postgres-1  | 2025-05-19 21:55:23.087 UTC [1603] LOG:  statement: COMMIT
  ```

  - [ ] Stress test populate dataset query with 'real' dataset (that is: `checks_{domain,mail}testreport (id, timestamp, domain, score)` dump, or anonymized set)

- [x] Use single `MERGE` instead of `DELETE + UPDATE`:
- [x] Use `OR UPDATE OF score ON` trigger

Note for the initial population: maybe `PARTITION BY domain ORDER BY id DESC` should be changed to `PARTITION BY domain ORDER BY timestamp DESC`, although the change will probably be minimal, but the current situation is ordered by timestamp.

comment.body:
Testing concluded:
- If the (page) cache is outdated, the view should run spiffy, it does not, this is mainly due to the slow counts.
- Even after adding an extra index on the `domain` field, the resulting Index Only Scans (that can run as a [Parallel Scan](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/parallel-query.html) by PostgreSQL) will run 'slow' (as in seconds) for tables with multi M records (see [PostgreSQL count performance reference](https://www.citusdata.com/blog/2016/10/12/count-performance/#reference)), these all run in serial in the (new) code (that is by Django, not talking about the [Parallel PostgreSQL](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/parallel-query.html) part), although running in parallel with async is probably not the hack desired (see [async Django](https://fly.io/django-beats/running-tasks-concurrently-in-django-asynchronous-views/#using-the-orm) since it might require raw SQL).

Steps forward:
- [ ] Create index on domain for test reports
- [ ] (Minor improvement of the trigger) Add `NEW.Score != OLD.Score` to Trigger (and make sure if both old and new are `NULL` the query of the trigger also does not execute, e.g. on registrar updates).
- [ ] Create some distinct_count model/table, with initial count fill for all 3 models, with total & fame + champions count
- [ ] Triggers on test reports to update total, triggers on fame to update fame:
    - [ ] Test report: on create, was there a earlier report, if not: update total +1, on delete/update domain (not sure if this is a valid case: check if there is still a report with this domain, if not: total -1.
    - [ ] Fame: on insert / update / delete: and for both site/mail: if old is null, fame +1, if new is null, fame -1
- [ ] Redo-testing with double the batch count (since the HoF SQL is not optional and 'enabled by default')
